e show follows a group of teenagers\u2014Mickey, Nita and Billy Joe\u2014who solve mysteries and crimes with their friend, [[Shmoo]], a friendly bulbous creature who can stretch and shape his body into any form he wants. The teens worked for Mighty Mysteries Comics.\n\n==Production==\nDuring the original NBC run, the program included a short segment called \"Sing Along With The Shmoo\". In a manner reminiscent of ''[[Screen Songs]]'', Shmoo became a [[bouncing ball (music)|bouncing ball]], providing visual guidance to song lyrics so that viewers could sing along with the cartoon.\n\n==Episodes==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#FFFFFF\"\n|- style=\"color:#FFFFFF\"\n! style=\"background:#000070; width:20px\"| N\u00ba\n! style=\"background:#000070\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#000070; width:135px\"| Airdate\n\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 1\n| Title = The Amazing Captain Mentor\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|9|22}}\n| ShortSummary = A superhero comes to town to capture and rehabilitate bank robbers...or does he?\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 2\n| Title = The Beast of Black Lake\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|9|29}}\n| ShortSummary = Black Lake is menaced by a serpentine monster that may or may not be real.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 3\n| Title = The Ber-Shmoo-Da Triangle\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|10|6}}\n| ShortSummary = The gang boards a plane bound for the Bermuda Triangle, unaware that their \"pilots\" are actually a pair of jewel thieves.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 4\n| Title = The Crystal Ball of Crime\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|10|13}}\n| ShortSummary = Madame Natasha is able to predict crimes before they're committed.  Billy Joe has a premonition of his own--that Madame Natasha herself will commit a robbery!\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 5\n| Title = Dr. Morton's Monster\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|10|20}}\n| ShortSummary = During a storm, a robot built by Dr. Morton seems to be creating havoc.  He's actually helping to repair damage, but the townspeople don't see it that way.  They cause the robot to go on a rampage, and only Shmoo can short it out.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 6\n| Title = The Energy Robbers from Space\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|10|27}}\n| ShortSummary = Aliens are stealing energy sources from a research lab.  With help from Professor Potts, the gang exposes the criminals.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 7\n| Title = The Flying Disc of Doom\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|11|3}}\n| ShortSummary = Aliens turn back time, and seem to turn a farmer's dog into a puppy.  But is there more to this strange turn of events?\n\n''Note:'' Shmoo creator Al Capp died of emphysema 2 days after this episode's telecast.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 8\n| Title = The Haunting of Atlantis\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|11|10}}\n| ShortSummary = Shmoo and company join a world famous oceanographer in his search for Atlantis, whose inhabitants don't exactly take kindly to intruders.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 9\n| Title = Monster Island\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|11|17}}\n| ShortSummary = A distress call brings the team out to Odyssey Island, where a Cyclops, Minotaur, and Medusa are running amok.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 10\n| Title = The Pyramid of Peril\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|11|24}}\n| ShortSummary = A billionaire is convinced a pyramid can make him young again.  Mickey, Nita, Billy Joe, and Shmoo expose the scam.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 11\n| Title = The Return of Dracula\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|12|1}}\n| ShortSummary = The gang discovers that Dracula is alive and well and living in Transylvania.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 12\n| Title = Swamp of Evil\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|12|8}} <sup>1</sup>\n| ShortSummary = The group ends up in a small town after getting lost during their vacation.  They realize someone's been dumping harmful chemicals in the swamp.  But who? And why?\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 13\n| Title = The Terror of the Trolls\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|12|15}} <sup>1</sup>\n| ShortSummary = An island is menaced by a horde of trolls.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 14\n| Title = The Valley Where Time Stood Still\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|12|22}} <sup>1</sup>\n| ShortSummary = While visiting a ranch out west, the kids and Shmoo discover a valley inhabited by cavemen and dinosaurs.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 15\n| Title = The Wail of the Banshee\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1979|12|29}} <sup>1</sup>\n| ShortSummary = A banshee is haunting the Dalton estate.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber = 16\n| Title = The Warlock of Voodoo Island\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|1980|1|5}} <sup>1</sup>\n| ShortSummary = Mickey's grandma, a lighthouse operator, is terrorized by a mysterious warlock.\n| LineColor = 000070\n}}\n|}\n*<sup>1</sup> These episodes were incorporated into the 90-minute package show ''[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]''\n\n==Voices==\n* [[Frank Welker]] - Shmoo\n* [[Dolores Cantu-Primo]] - Nita\n* [[Bill Idelson]] - Mickey\n* [[Chuck McCann]] - Billy Joe\n* Additional voices: Joe Baker, [[Daws Butler]], [[Bob Hastings]], [[Don Messick]], [[Jim MacGeorge]], [[Margaret McIntyre]], [[Ginny McSwain]], [[Hal Smith (actor)|Hal Smith]], [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]], [[Janet Waldo]], [[Bill Woodson]]\n\n==Broadcast history==\n''The New Shmoo'' originally aired in these following formats on [[NBC]]:\n\n*'''''The New Shmoo''''' (September 22, 1979 - December 1, 1979)\n*'''''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo''''' (December 8, 1979 - November 15, 1980)\n\n==Production credits==\n* Executive Producers: [[William Hanna]] and [[Joseph Barbera]]\n* Producers: [[Alex Lovy]] and Art Scott\n* Directors: Oscar Dufau, [[Ray Patterson (animator)|Ray Patterson]], [[Carl Urbano]], [[George Gordon (animator)|George Gordon]]\n* Story Supervisor: Jim Ryan\n* Story Editor: [[Chuck Menville]]\n* Story: Gene Ayres, Doug Booth, Art Browne, Jr., [[Buzz Dixon]], Donald F. Glut, Len Janson, Dale Kirby, Glenn Leopold, [[Chuck Menville]], J. Michael Reaves, Jim Ryan\n* Story Direction: [[Don R. Christensen|Don Christensen]], Jan Green\n* Recording Director: Art Scott\n* Voices: [[Joe Baker (actor)|Joe Baker]], [[Daws Butler]], [[Bob Hastings]], [[Bill Idelson]], [[Don Messick]], [[Chuck McCann]], [[Jim MacGeorge]], [[Margaret McIntyre]], [[Ginny McSwain]], Dolores Cantu-Primo, [[Hal Smith (actor)|Hal Smith]], [[John Stephenson (actor)|John Stephenson]], [[Janet Waldo]], [[Frank Welker]], [[Bill Woodson]]\n* Graphics: Iraj Paran, Tom Wogatzke\n* Title Design: Don Sheppard\n* Musical Director: [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n* Musical Supervisor: Paul DeKorte\n* Creative Producer: [[Iwao Takamoto]]\n* Design Supervisor: Bob Singer\n* Character Design: Jack Kirby, Don Morgan, Mike Sekowsky, Sandra Young\n* Layout Supervisor: Don Morgan\n* Key Layout: [[Mark Kirkland]]\n* Layout: Kurt Anderson, Tom Bird, Aaron Crippen, Bob Foster, Linda Harris, Mike Hodgson, Ray Jacobs, Allen Larson, Jim McLean, Phil Ortiz, Glenn Schmitz, Dave Stevens\n* Animation Supervisors: Bob Goe, Bill Keil, Jay Sarbry, Ken Southworth\n* Animation: [[Robert Alvarez]], Frank Andrina, Colin Baker, Anne Marie Bardwell, Ed Barge, Bob Bemiller, Robert Bransford, James Brummett, Oliver Callahan, Roger Chiasson, John Conning, Daniel De La Vega, Joan Drake, Judith Ann Drake, Gail Finkeldei, Hugh Fraser, Al Gaivoto, [[Jeff Hall (animator)|Jeff Hall]], Bob Hathcock, Fred Hellmich, Bill Hutten, Aundre Knuston, Teresa Loewy, Hicks Lokey, Tony Love, Mauro Maressa, Burton Medall, Tran Vu Minh, Ken Muse, Eduardo Olivares, Margaret Parkes, Lester Pegues, Jr., Harry Rasmussen, Morey Reden, Joel Seibel, Leo Sullivan, Richard Trueblood, Robert Tyler, John Walker, Allen Wilzbach\n* Assistant Animation Supervisor: Rick Leon\n* Background Supervisor: Al Gmuer\n* Backgrounds: Lorraine Andrina, Fernando Arce, Greg Battes, Dario Campanile, Gil Dicicco, Dennis Durrell, Fla Ferreira, Martin Forte, Bob Gentle, Bonnie Goodknight, Al Gmuer, Ann Guenther, Tom Hames, James Hegedus, Eric Heschong, Jim Hickey, Mike Humphries, Andy Phillipson, Bill Proctor, Viviven Rhyan, Jeff Richards, Cal Titus, Dennis Veinzelos\n* Checking and Scene Planning: Cindy Smith\n* Xerography: Star Wirth\n* Ink and Paint Supervisor: Alison Victory\n* Sound Direction: Richard Olson, Bill Getty\n* Camera: Ross Avery, Bob Berry, Allen Childs, Marc Debrilande, Candy Edwards, Curt Hall, Mike Kane, Jerry Mills, Neil Viker, Roy Wade, Brandy Whittington, Jerry Whittington\n* Supervising Film Editor: Larry C. Cowan\n* Dubbing Supervisor: Pat Foley\n* Music Editor: Terry Moore\n* Effects Editors: Mark Mangini, Karla McGregor\n* Show Editor: Gil Iverson\n* Negative Consultant: William E. DeBoer\n* Production Manager: Jayne Barbera\n* Post Production Supervisor: Joed Eaton\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0292415}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0298649|title=Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo}}\n*{{tv.com show|fred-and-barney-meet-the-shmoo|Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo}}\n*[http://www.bcdb.com/cartoons/Hanna-Barbera_Studios/D-F/Fred_and_Barney_Meet_the_Shmoo/index.html ''Fred and Barney Meet the Shmoo''] at the [[The Big Cartoon DataBase|Big Cartoon DataBase]]\n\n{{Li'l Abner}}\n{{Children's programming on NBC in the 1970s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Shmoo}}\n[[Category:1979 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American children's animated mystery television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:American animated television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Li'l Abner]]\n[[Category:Television series by Hanna-Barbera]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_Shmoo"}
{"title_page": "Semni Karouzou", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek archaeologist and art historian}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name           = Semni Karouzou\n| image          = Semni_Karouzou.jpg\n| birth_name     = Polysemni Papaspyridi\n| birth_date     = {{birth year|1897}}\n| birth_place    = [[Tripoli, Greece]]\n| death_date     = {{death year and age|1994|1897}}\n| occupation     = Archaeologist and curator\n| discipline     = Greek Archaeology\n| sub_discipline = Ceramics\n| workplaces     = [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens]]\n}}\n\n'''Semni Papaspyridi-Karouzou''' (1897\u20131994) was a [[Classical archaeology|classical archaeologist]] who specialized in the study of [[pottery]] from [[ancient Greece]]. She was the first woman to join the [[Greek Archaeological Service]], and worked as Curator of ceramic collections at the [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens|National Archaeological Museum in Athens]] for over thirty years. She has been described by the archaeologists [[Marianna Nikolaidou]] and [[Dimitra Kokkinidouas]] as \"perhaps the most important woman in Greek archaeology\", and by the newspaper ''[[To Vima]]'' as \"the last representative of the generation of great archaeologists\".<ref name=\":3\">Marianna Nikolaidou & Dimitra Kokkinidou (1998), 'Greek women in archaeology: an untold story', in Margarita D\u00edaz-Andreu & Marie Louise Stig Sorensen (eds), ''Excavating Women: A History of Women in European Archaeology'' (London/New York: Routledge), pp.235-265.</ref>\n\n== Early and personal life ==\nPolysemni Papaspyridi, who went by Semni, was born in 1897 in [[Tripoli, Greece]].{{Efn|1897 is given as her birth date by Nikolaidou & Kokkinidou 1998; other sources give it as 1898 [[https://www.archetai.gr/images/persons/Semni_Karouzou.pdf]] or 1889 [[https://argolikivivliothiki.gr/2010/09/30/%ce%ba%ce%b1%cf%81%ce%bf%cf%8d%ce%b6%ce%bf%cf%85-%e2%80%93-%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%83%cf%80%cf%85%cf%81%ce%af%ce%b4%ce%b7-%cf%83%ce%ad%ce%bc%ce%bd%ce%b7-1889-8-%ce%b4%ce%b5%ce%ba%ce%b5%ce%bc/]]}} Her father was a military officer, and her mother the French-educated daughter of a judge; her family moved frequently due to her father's career, finally settling in [[Athens]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://argolikivivliothiki.gr/2010/09/30/%ce%ba%ce%b1%cf%81%ce%bf%cf%8d%ce%b6%ce%bf%cf%85-%e2%80%93-%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%83%cf%80%cf%85%cf%81%ce%af%ce%b4%ce%b7-%cf%83%ce%ad%ce%bc%ce%bd%ce%b7-1889-8-%ce%b4%ce%b5%ce%ba%ce%b5%ce%bc/|title=\u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5 \u2013 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03b4\u03b7 \u03a3\u03ad\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7 (1889 \u2013 8 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 1994)|date=2010-09-30|website=\u0391\u03a1\u0393\u039f\u039b\u0399\u039a\u0397 \u0391\u03a1\u03a7\u0395\u0399\u0391\u039a\u0397 \u0392\u0399\u0392\u039b\u0399\u039f\u0398\u0397\u039a\u0397 \u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u039f\u03a1\u0399\u0391\u03a3 \u039a\u0391\u0399 \u03a0\u039f\u039b\u0399\u03a4\u0399\u03a3\u039c\u039f\u03a5|language=el|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> She took the name Papaspyridi-Karouzou on her marriage in 1930 to [[Christos Karouzos]] (1900-1967), also an archaeologist.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Education and early archaeological career ==\nKarouzou studied archaeology at the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]], where she was taught by the archaeologist [[Christos Tsountas]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.archetai.gr/images/persons/Semni_Karouzou.pdf|title=Semni Karouzou|last=|first=|date=|website=Archaeological Society at Athens|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She joined the [[Greek Archaeological Service]] in 1921 as a curator of antiquities at the [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens|National Archaeological Museum of Athens]], becoming the first woman to do so.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Rolley|first=Claude|date=1995|title=Semni Karouzou (1898-1994)|url=|journal=Revue Arch\u00e9ologique|volume=|pages=333\u2013335|via=}}</ref> Karouzou then worked on excavations at [[Aegean civilization|Bronze Age]] sites at [[Heraklion|Herakleion]], on [[Crete]], and the [[Classical Greece|classical]] site of [[Eretria]], on [[Euboea]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://trowelblazers.com/semni-karouzou-visible-resistance/|title=Semni Karouzou: Visible Resistance|last=Hardy|first=Sam|date=|website=TrowelBlazers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1928, she (along with Christos Karouzos) was awarded a [[Humboldt fellowship|Humboldt Fellowship]] to study at the universities of [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|Munich]] and [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin]]; when she returned to Greece in 1930 she was promoted to the post of Ephor of Antiquities (head of an ephorate, an archaeological administrative district), an achievement described as a \"feminist victory\" by the activist [[Avra Theodoropoulou]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Karouzou held the post in Thessaly and then in the [[Argolis|Argolid]], where she excavated tombs from the Mycenaean and classical periods;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1933-1935|title=Anaskafi tafon tou Argous (Excavation of tombs at Argos)|url=|journal=Archaiologikon Deltion|volume=15|pages=16\u201353|via=}}</ref> worked in [[Epidaurus|ancient Epidaurus]]; and worked to preserve historic buildings in the town of [[Nafplio]], where she later published a guide.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Semni Karouzou, \u03a4\u03bf \u039d\u03b1\u03cd\u03c0\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf [Nafplio]. \u0395\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a4\u03c1\u03ac\u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, 1979.</ref>\n\n== Curatorial work ==\nIn 1933, Karouzou became curator of the ceramic collections at the [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens|National Archaeological Museum in Athens]], a post she held for over thirty years (until 1964). For most of this period women were prohibited from joining the Archaeological Service under a law introduced by the dictator [[Ioannis Metaxas]] in 1936, and existing women members were refused promotion to the highest posts as museum directors or ephors.<ref name=\":3\" /> Karouzou's work included reorganising the collections - identifying artefacts which had not been properly catalogued, recording them, and arranging new displays{{Em dash}}work which she described as 'invisible service'.<ref name=\":4\">Semni Karouzou (1984), \u0392\u03b9\u03ce\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1 (Experiences and memorials), \u0397\u039f\u03a1\u039f\u03a3 2.2, pp.1-61: quoted in Nikolaidou & Kokkinidou (1998)</ref> She also wrote extensively on the museum's collections of ceramics<ref>{{Cite book|title=Corpus Vasorum Antiquorum. Gr\u00e8ce 2: Ath\u00e8nes, Mus\u00e9e National 2|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=|year=1954|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> and stone monuments,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1952|title=Archaika mnimeia tou Ethnikou Mouseiou (Archaic monuments of the National Museum)|url=|journal=Archaiologiki Ephemeris|volume=|pages=137\u201366|via=}}</ref> as well as on new archaeological discoveries.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1945|title=Vases from odos Pandrosou|url=|journal=Journal of Hellenic Studies|volume=65|pages=38\u201344|doi=10.2307/626338|jstor=626338}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Angeia tou Anagyrountos|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=|year=1963|isbn=|location=Athens|pages=}}</ref> Her monograph on the [[Amasis Painter]], a major painter of [[Black-figure pottery|Attic black-figure pottery]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Amasis Painter|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1956|isbn=|location=Oxford|pages=}}</ref> was described by a reviewer as \"a scholarly and valuable study\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cook|first=R. M.|date=1957|title=Semni Karouzou: The Amasis Painter. Pp. xii + 46; 44 plates. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1956. Cloth, 75s. net.|journal=The Classical Review|language=en|volume=7|issue=3\u20134|pages=271\u2013272|doi=10.1017/S0009840X00177571|issn=1464-3561}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[Axis occupation of Greece|Axis invasion of Greece in 1940]], Karouzou and her husband (along with other archaeologists, museum guards, and their families) packed away the museum's collections for safety during [[World War II]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Karouzou later recalled that \"It was with pride for our people that I was assured, in the end of the war when the boxes were opened and the antiquities received, despite [the] fatally insufficient supervision [of the packing process] not a single gold object, no precious gem was missing\".<ref name=\":4\" /> When Athens was occupied by the German army in 1941, the Karouzous were the only archaeologists in Greece to withdraw their membership of the [[German Archaeological Institute]] in protest.<ref name=\":0\" /> After the end of World War II, they were responsible for reinstalling the museum collections, using the catalogues Karouzou had made; this reinstallation was completed in 1947.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Career post-retirement ==\nIn 1964, Karouzou turned 67 and was forced to retire from the Archaeological Service due to a new law imposing an age limit on civil servants. Three years later, the [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974|Greek military junta]] came to power, a month after Karouzou's husband died of a heart attack. As a political liberal, Karouzou was labelled a [[political dissident|dissident]] and banned from accessing material in the museum by the junta-appointed General Director of Antiquities, [[Spyridon Marinatos]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Unable to carry out her research on the museum's collections{{Em dash}}a situation which she described as \"a shameless exclusion from the places of research of unpublished ancient works\"<ref name=\":4\" />{{Em dash}}she secretly left the country by boat to stay at the German Institute in Rome and then in Munich by invitation from colleagues. On her return, she was accused of being a communist and prohibited from leaving the country again. An international outcry arose over this prohibition; a letter written by a group of British archaeologists (including [[Bernard Ashmole]] and [[John Boardman (art historian)|John Boardman]]) was published on the front page of ''[[The Times]].<ref>ANDREWES, A., et al. \"A passport refused.\" ''Times'', 9 Dec. 1970, p. 11. ''The Times Digital Archive'', <nowiki>https://link-gale-com.ezp.lib.cam.ac.uk/apps/doc/CS185955209/TTDA?u=cambuni&sid=TTDA&xid=122919b2</nowiki>. Accessed 20 Apr. 2020.</ref>'' This led to Karouzou being allowed to leave the country to spend time visiting exiled Greeks in Rome and [[Lyon]] and to work as an invited scholar at the universities of [[University of T\u00fcbingen|T\u00fcbingen]] and [[University of Geneva|Geneva]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFollowing the fall of the junta in 1974, Karouzou was able to return to Greece and become chair of the Greek arm of the 'Lexicon Iconographicarum Mythologicae Classicae' ('Lexicon of the Iconographies of Classical Mythology').<ref name=\":3\" /> From 1975 to 1977, she was vice president of the [[Archaeological Society of Athens|Archaeological Society at Athens]],<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> and she was made president of the International Congress of Classical Archaeology in 1983.<ref name=\":5\" /> She was awarded honorary doctorates from the Universities of [[University of Lyon|Lyon]], [[University of T\u00fcbingen|T\u00fcbingen]], and [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki|Thessaloniki]] for her scholarship and contributions to the field.<ref name=\":3\" /> In total, Karouzou published twenty books and over one hundred and twenty articles during the course of her career; she also contributed to public access to archaeology through the publication of guidebooks to the National Archaeological Museum and to archaeological sites.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=National Museum: Illustrated Guide to the Museum|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0391\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd|year=2000|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\nArchaeologists Nikolaidou and Kokkinidou (specialists in the history of Greek archaeology) refer to her \"continuous scholarly effort, broad intellectual perspective, social contribution and democratic sensitivity\" and the innovative nature of her approach to ancient artefacts, particularly iconography on pottery, by which she \"moved beyond the images to real people, their everyday life, attitudes and ideologies\".<ref name=\":3\" /> Karouzou defined her own research methodology as attempting to reveal \"the invisible meaning of ancient works\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1945-1947|title=Ai epta thygateres tou Atlantos (The seven daughters of Atlas)|url=|journal=Archaiologiki Ephemeris|volume=|pages=22\u201336|via=quoted in Nikolaidou & Kokkinidou (1998)}}</ref>\n\nKarouzou died in December 1994. In its announcement of her death, the Greek newspaper ''[[To Vima]]'' called her 'the last representative of the generation of great archaeologists'.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* National Museum: Illustrated Guide to the Museum, {{lang|el|\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0391\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd}}, 2000.\n* {{lang|el|\u0392\u03b9\u03ce\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1}} (Experiences and memorials), {{lang|el|\u0397\u039f\u03a1\u039f\u03a3}} 2.2, 1984, pp. 1\u201361\n* Nauplion (in Greek: {{lang|el|\u03a4\u03bf \u039d\u03b1\u03cd\u03c0\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf}}). {{lang|el|\u0395\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a4\u03c1\u03ac\u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2}}, 1979.\n*''The Amasis Painter'', Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1956''.''\n* ''Corpus Vasorum Antiquorum. Gr\u00e8ce 2: Ath\u00e8nes, Mus\u00e9e National 2'', Paris, 1954 (publication of the National Museum's classical vase collections)\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://trowelblazers.com/semni-karouzou-visible-resistance/ Trowelblazers] article\n* [https://argolikivivliothiki.gr/2010/09/30/%CE%BA%CE%B1%CF%81%CE%BF%CF%8D%CE%B6%CE%BF%CF%85-%E2%80%93-%CF%80%CE%B1%CF%80%CE%B1%CF%83%CF%80%CF%85%CF%81%CE%AF%CE%B4%CE%B7-%CF%83%CE%AD%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7-1889-8-%CE%B4%CE%B5%CE%BA%CE%B5%CE%BC/ Argolikos Archival Library of History and Culture] (in Greek)\n* [https://www.archetai.gr/images/persons/Semni_Karouzou.pdf Archaeological Society at Athens] (in Greek)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karouzou, Semni}}\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Greek archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Classical archaeologists]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Women curators]]\n[[Category:Greek women]]\n[[Category:Greek curators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek archaeologist and art historian}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| name           = Semni Karouzou\n| image          = Semni_Karouzou.jpg\n| birth_name     = Polysemni Papaspyridi\n| birth_date     = {{birth year|1897}}\n| birth_place    = [[Tripoli, Greece]]\n| death_date     = {{death year and age|1994|1897}}\n| occupation     = Archaeologist and curator\n| discipline     = Greek Archaeology\n| sub_discipline = Ceramics\n| workplaces     = [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens]]\n}}\n\n'''Semni Papaspyridi-Karouzou''' (1897\u20131994) was a [[Classical archaeology|classical archaeologist]] who specialized in the study of [[pottery]] from [[ancient Greece]]. She was the first woman to join the [[Greek Archaeological Service]], and worked as Curator of ceramic collections at the [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens|National Archaeological Museum in Athens]] for over thirty years. She has been described by the archaeologists [[Marianna Nikolaidou]] and [[Dimitra Kokkinidouas]] as \"perhaps the most important woman in Greek archaeology\", and by the newspaper ''[[To Vima]]'' as \"the last representative of the generation of great archaeologists\".<ref name=\":3\">Marianna Nikolaidou & Dimitra Kokkinidou (1998), 'Greek women in archaeology: an untold story', in Margarita D\u00edaz-Andreu & Marie Louise Stig Sorensen (eds), ''Excavating Women: A History of Women in European Archaeology'' (London/New York: Routledge), pp.235-265.</ref>\n\n== Early and personal life ==\nPolysemni Papaspyridi, who went by Semni, was born in 1897 in [[Tripoli, Greece]].{{Efn|1897 is given as her birth date by Nikolaidou & Kokkinidou 1998; other sources give it as 1898 [[https://www.archetai.gr/images/persons/Semni_Karouzou.pdf]] or 1889 [[https://argolikivivliothiki.gr/2010/09/30/%ce%ba%ce%b1%cf%81%ce%bf%cf%8d%ce%b6%ce%bf%cf%85-%e2%80%93-%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%83%cf%80%cf%85%cf%81%ce%af%ce%b4%ce%b7-%cf%83%ce%ad%ce%bc%ce%bd%ce%b7-1889-8-%ce%b4%ce%b5%ce%ba%ce%b5%ce%bc/]]}} Her father was a military officer, and her mother the French-educated daughter of a judge; her family moved frequently due to her father's career, finally settling in [[Athens]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://argolikivivliothiki.gr/2010/09/30/%ce%ba%ce%b1%cf%81%ce%bf%cf%8d%ce%b6%ce%bf%cf%85-%e2%80%93-%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%80%ce%b1%cf%83%cf%80%cf%85%cf%81%ce%af%ce%b4%ce%b7-%cf%83%ce%ad%ce%bc%ce%bd%ce%b7-1889-8-%ce%b4%ce%b5%ce%ba%ce%b5%ce%bc/|title=\u039a\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03b6\u03bf\u03c5 \u2013 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c0\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03b4\u03b7 \u03a3\u03ad\u03bc\u03bd\u03b7 (1889 \u2013 8 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03b5\u03bc\u03b2\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 1994)|date=2010-09-30|website=\u0391\u03a1\u0393\u039f\u039b\u0399\u039a\u0397 \u0391\u03a1\u03a7\u0395\u0399\u0391\u039a\u0397 \u0392\u0399\u0392\u039b\u0399\u039f\u0398\u0397\u039a\u0397 \u0399\u03a3\u03a4\u039f\u03a1\u0399\u0391\u03a3 \u039a\u0391\u0399 \u03a0\u039f\u039b\u0399\u03a4\u0399\u03a3\u039c\u039f\u03a5|language=el|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref> She took the name Papaspyridi-Karouzou on her marriage in 1930 to [[Christos Karouzos]] (1900-1967), also an archaeologist.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Education and early archaeological career ==\nKarouzou studied archaeology at the [[National and Kapodistrian University of Athens|University of Athens]], where she was taught by the archaeologist [[Christos Tsountas]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.archetai.gr/images/persons/Semni_Karouzou.pdf|title=Semni Karouzou|last=|first=|date=|website=Archaeological Society at Athens|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> She joined the [[Greek Archaeological Service]] in 1921 as a curator of antiquities at the [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens|National Archaeological Museum of Athens]], becoming the first woman to do so.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Rolley|first=Claude|date=1995|title=Semni Karouzou (1898-1994)|url=|journal=Revue Arch\u00e9ologique|volume=|pages=333\u2013335|via=}}</ref> Karouzou then worked on excavations at [[Aegean civilization|Bronze Age]] sites at [[Heraklion|Herakleion]], on [[Crete]], and the [[Classical Greece|classical]] site of [[Eretria]], on [[Euboea]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://trowelblazers.com/semni-karouzou-visible-resistance/|title=Semni Karouzou: Visible Resistance|last=Hardy|first=Sam|date=|website=TrowelBlazers|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1928, she (along with Christos Karouzos) was awarded a [[Humboldt fellowship|Humboldt Fellowship]] to study at the universities of [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|Munich]] and [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Berlin]]; when she returned to Greece in 1930 she was promoted to the post of Ephor of Antiquities (head of an ephorate, an archaeological administrative district), an achievement described as a \"feminist victory\" by the activist [[Avra Theodoropoulou]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Karouzou held the post in Thessaly and then in the [[Argolis|Argolid]], where she excavated tombs from the Mycenaean and classical periods;<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1933-1935|title=Anaskafi tafon tou Argous (Excavation of tombs at Argos)|url=|journal=Archaiologikon Deltion|volume=15|pages=16\u201353|via=}}</ref> worked in [[Epidaurus|ancient Epidaurus]]; and worked to preserve historic buildings in the town of [[Nafplio]], where she later published a guide.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>Semni Karouzou, \u03a4\u03bf \u039d\u03b1\u03cd\u03c0\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf [Nafplio]. \u0395\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a4\u03c1\u03ac\u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2, 1979.</ref>\n\n== Curatorial work ==\nIn 1933, Karouzou became curator of the ceramic collections at the [[National Archaeological Museum, Athens|National Archaeological Museum in Athens]], a post she held for over thirty years (until 1964). For most of this period women were prohibited from joining the Archaeological Service under a law introduced by the dictator [[Ioannis Metaxas]] in 1936, and existing women members were refused promotion to the highest posts as museum directors or ephors.<ref name=\":3\" /> Karouzou's work included reorganising the collections - identifying artefacts which had not been properly catalogued, recording them, and arranging new displays{{Em dash}}work which she described as 'invisible service'.<ref name=\":4\">Semni Karouzou (1984), \u0392\u03b9\u03ce\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1 (Experiences and memorials), \u0397\u039f\u03a1\u039f\u03a3 2.2, pp.1-61: quoted in Nikolaidou & Kokkinidou (1998)</ref> She also wrote extensively on the museum's collections of ceramics<ref>{{Cite book|title=Corpus Vasorum Antiquorum. Gr\u00e8ce 2: Ath\u00e8nes, Mus\u00e9e National 2|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=|year=1954|isbn=|location=Paris|pages=}}</ref> and stone monuments,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1952|title=Archaika mnimeia tou Ethnikou Mouseiou (Archaic monuments of the National Museum)|url=|journal=Archaiologiki Ephemeris|volume=|pages=137\u201366|via=}}</ref> as well as on new archaeological discoveries.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1945|title=Vases from odos Pandrosou|url=|journal=Journal of Hellenic Studies|volume=65|pages=38\u201344|doi=10.2307/626338|jstor=626338}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Angeia tou Anagyrountos|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=|year=1963|isbn=|location=Athens|pages=}}</ref> Her monograph on the [[Amasis Painter]], a major painter of [[Black-figure pottery|Attic black-figure pottery]],<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Amasis Painter|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=Clarendon Press|year=1956|isbn=|location=Oxford|pages=}}</ref> was described by a reviewer as \"a scholarly and valuable study\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cook|first=R. M.|date=1957|title=Semni Karouzou: The Amasis Painter. Pp. xii + 46; 44 plates. Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1956. Cloth, 75s. net.|journal=The Classical Review|language=en|volume=7|issue=3\u20134|pages=271\u2013272|doi=10.1017/S0009840X00177571|issn=1464-3561}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[Axis occupation of Greece|Axis invasion of Greece in 1940]], Karouzou and her husband (along with other archaeologists, museum guards, and their families) packed away the museum's collections for safety during [[World War II]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> Karouzou later recalled that \"It was with pride for our people that I was assured, in the end of the war when the boxes were opened and the antiquities received, despite [the] fatally insufficient supervision [of the packing process] not a single gold object, no precious gem was missing\".<ref name=\":4\" /> When Athens was occupied by the German army in 1941, the Karouzous were the only archaeologists in Greece to withdraw their membership of the [[German Archaeological Institute]] in protest.<ref name=\":0\" /> After the end of World War II, they were responsible for reinstalling the museum collections, using the catalogues Karouzou had made; this reinstallation was completed in 1947.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Career post-retirement ==\nIn 1964, Karouzou turned 67 and was forced to retire from the Archaeological Service due to a new law imposing an age limit on civil servants. Three years later, the [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974|Greek military junta]] came to power, a month after Karouzou's husband died of a heart attack. As a political liberal, Karouzou was labelled a [[political dissident|dissident]] and banned from accessing material in the museum by the junta-appointed General Director of Antiquities, [[Spyridon Marinatos]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Unable to carry out her research on the museum's collections{{Em dash}}a situation which she described as \"a shameless exclusion from the places of research of unpublished ancient works\"<ref name=\":4\" />{{Em dash}}she secretly left the country by boat to stay at the German Institute in Rome and then in Munich by invitation from colleagues. On her return, she was accused of being a communist and prohibited from leaving the country again. An international outcry arose over this prohibition; a letter written by a group of British archaeologists (including [[Bernard Ashmole]] and [[John Boardman (art historian)|John Boardman]]) was published on the front page of ''[[The Times]].<ref>ANDREWES, A., et al. \"A passport refused.\" ''Times'', 9 Dec. 1970, p. 11. ''The Times Digital Archive'', <nowiki>https://link-gale-com.ezp.lib.cam.ac.uk/apps/doc/CS185955209/TTDA?u=cambuni&sid=TTDA&xid=122919b2</nowiki>. Accessed 20 Apr. 2020.</ref>'' This led to Karouzou being allowed to leave the country to spend time visiting exiled Greeks in Rome and [[Lyon]] and to work as an invited scholar at the universities of [[University of T\u00fcbingen|T\u00fcbingen]] and [[University of Geneva|Geneva]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nFollowing the fall of the junta in 1974, Karouzou was able to return to Greece and become chair of the Greek arm of the 'Lexicon Iconographicarum Mythologicae Classicae' ('Lexicon of the Iconographies of Classical Mythology').<ref name=\":3\" /> From 1975 to 1977, she was vice president of the [[Archaeological Society of Athens|Archaeological Society at Athens]],<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> and she was made president of the International Congress of Classical Archaeology in 1983.<ref name=\":5\" /> She was awarded honorary doctorates from the Universities of [[University of Lyon|Lyon]], [[University of T\u00fcbingen|T\u00fcbingen]], and [[Aristotle University of Thessaloniki|Thessaloniki]] for her scholarship and contributions to the field.<ref name=\":3\" /> In total, Karouzou published twenty books and over one hundred and twenty articles during the course of her career; she also contributed to public access to archaeology through the publication of guidebooks to the National Archaeological Museum and to archaeological sites.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite book|title=National Museum: Illustrated Guide to the Museum|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|publisher=\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0391\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd|year=2000|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\nArchaeologists Nikolaidou and Kokkinidou (specialists in the history of Greek archaeology) refer to her \"continuous scholarly effort, broad intellectual perspective, social contribution and democratic sensitivity\" and the innovative nature of her approach to ancient artefacts, particularly iconography on pottery, by which she \"moved beyond the images to real people, their everyday life, attitudes and ideologies\".<ref name=\":3\" /> Karouzou defined her own research methodology as attempting to reveal \"the invisible meaning of ancient works\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karouzou|first=Semni|date=1945-1947|title=Ai epta thygateres tou Atlantos (The seven daughters of Atlas)|url=|journal=Archaiologiki Ephemeris|volume=|pages=22\u201336|via=quoted in Nikolaidou & Kokkinidou (1998)}}</ref>\n\nKarouzou died in December 1994. In its announcement of her death, the Greek newspaper ''[[To Vima]]'' called her 'the last representative of the generation of great archaeologists'.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Selected publications ==\n\n* National Museum: Illustrated Guide to the Museum, {{lang|el|\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0391\u03b8\u03b7\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd}}, 2000.\n* {{lang|el|\u0392\u03b9\u03ce\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bc\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03cc\u03c3\u03c5\u03bd\u03b1}} (Experiences and memorials), {{lang|el|\u0397\u039f\u03a1\u039f\u03a3}} 2.2, 1984, pp. 1\u201361\n* Nauplion (in Greek: {{lang|el|\u03a4\u03bf \u039d\u03b1\u03cd\u03c0\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf}}). {{lang|el|\u0395\u03bc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03a4\u03c1\u03ac\u03c0\u03b5\u03b6\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2}}, 1979.\n* \"'The Amasis Painter'', Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1956.\n* ''Corpus Vasorum Antiquorum. Gr\u00e8ce 2: Ath\u00e8nes, Mus\u00e9e National 2'', Paris, 1954 (publication of the National Museum's classical vase collections)\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://trowelblazers.com/semni-karouzou-visible-resistance/ Trowelblazers] article\n* [https://argolikivivliothiki.gr/2010/09/30/%CE%BA%CE%B1%CF%81%CE%BF%CF%8D%CE%B6%CE%BF%CF%85-%E2%80%93-%CF%80%CE%B1%CF%80%CE%B1%CF%83%CF%80%CF%85%CF%81%CE%AF%CE%B4%CE%B7-%CF%83%CE%AD%CE%BC%CE%BD%CE%B7-1889-8-%CE%B4%CE%B5%CE%BA%CE%B5%CE%BC/ Argolikos Archival Library of History and Culture] (in Greek)\n* [https://www.archetai.gr/images/persons/Semni_Karouzou.pdf Archaeological Society at Athens] (in Greek)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Karouzou, Semni}}\n[[Category:Women archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Greek archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Classical archaeologists]]\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1994 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Women curators]]\n[[Category:Greek women]]\n[[Category:Greek curators]]\n", "name_user": "Eritha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected publications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semni_Karouzou"}
{"title_page": "Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)", "text_new": "{{about|the original name of the Latter Day Saint (LDS) church founded by Joseph Smith|other LDS and non\u2013LDS denominations that use \"Church of Christ\"|Church of Christ (disambiguation)}}\n{{redirects|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints|the present-day LDS Church|The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|the present-day Strangite church|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite)}}\n\n[[File:Peter whitmer log home.JPG|thumb|A reconstruction of the original Peter Whitmer home in Fayette, New York.]]\nThe '''Church of Christ''' was the original name of the [[Latter Day Saint]] church founded by [[Joseph Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sos.mo.gov/archives/resources/mormon|title=The Missouri Mormon War|website=www.sos.mo.gov}}</ref> Organized informally in 1829 in  [[New York (state)|New York]] and then formally on April 6, 1830, it was the first organization to implement the principles found in Smith's newly published [[Book of Mormon]], and thus represents the formal beginning of the [[Latter Day Saint movement]]. Later names for this organization included the '''Church of the Latter Day Saints''' (by 1834 resolution),<ref name = 1834name>[http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/NCMP1820-1846/id/5889 \"Minutes of a Conference\"], ''[[Evening and Morning Star]]'', vol. 2, no. 20, p. 160 (May 1832).</ref> the '''Church of Jesus Christ''',<ref name = othernames>[[Joseph Smith]] ([[B. H. Roberts]] (ed.)) ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' vol. 3, p. 24, footnote.</ref> the '''Church of God''',<ref name = othernames/> the '''Church of Christ of Latter Day Saints''',<ref name = anderson>[[Richard Lloyd Anderson]], [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1979/01/i-have-a-question \"I Have a Question: What changes have been made in the name of the Church?\"], ''[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]'', January 1979.</ref><ref name=black>[[Susan Easton Black]], [http://eom.byu.edu/index.php/Name_of_the_Church \"Name of the Church\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521034958/http://eom.byu.edu/index.php/Name_of_the_Church |date=2014-05-21 }} in [[Daniel H. Ludlow]] ed., ''[[Encyclopedia of Mormonism]]'' (Macmillan: New York, 1992) p. 979.</ref> and the '''Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints'''<!-- Do not change this name to \"The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\". In the original text of the revelation, as referenced in this article, Smith wrote the name of the church \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" --> (by an 1838 revelation).<ref name = 1838name1>''Manuscript History of the Church'', LDS Church Archives, book A-1, p. 37; reproduced in Dean C. Jessee (comp.) (1989). ''The Papers of Joseph Smith: Autobiographical and Historical Writings'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Book) '''1''':302\u201303.</ref><ref name = 1838name2>H. Michael Marquardt and [[Wesley P. Walters]] (1994). ''Inventing Mormonism: Tradition and the Historical Record'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books) p. 160.</ref>\n\nSmith and his associates asserted that the Church of Christ was a [[Restoration (Latter Day Saints)|restoration]] of the 1st-century [[Christianity|Christian]] church, which Smith claimed had fallen from God's favor and authority because of what he called a \"[[Great Apostasy]]\".  After [[Death of Joseph Smith|Smith's death]] in 1844, there was a [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|crisis of authority]], with the majority of the members following [[Brigham Young]] to [[Utah Territory]], but with several smaller denominations remaining in Illinois or settling in Missouri and in other states. Each of the churches that resulted from this [[Schism (religion)|schism]] considers itself to be the rightful continuation of Smith's original \"Church of Christ\", regardless of the name they may currently bear ([[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] <!-- \"LDS Church\" is in accordance with the Wikipedia Manual of Style, and disagreements should be addressed at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Latter_Day_Saints. Any change made to \"LDS Church\" will be reverted. -->(LDS Church), [[Community of Christ]], [[The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite)]], [[Church of Christ (Temple Lot)]], etc.).\n\nThis church is unrelated to other bodies bearing the same name, including the [[United Church of Christ]], a [[Reformed churches|Reformed]] church body, and the [[Churches of Christ]], an offshoot of the [[Restoration movement|Campbellite movement]]. Today, there are several Latter Day Saint churches called \"Church of Christ\", largely within the [[Hedrickite]] branch of the movement.\n\n==Doctrinal development prior to 1830==\nThe first Latter Day Saint references to the \"church of Christ\" are found in passages of the [[Book of Mormon]] that Smith dictated from April to June 1829. During the course of this dictation, the outlines for a community of believers or church structure gradually became apparent. Such a structure would have authority from God, ordinances such as [[Baptism (Latter Day Saints)|baptism]], and ordained [[Priesthood (Mormonism)|clergy]]. Some time in April 1829, Smith dictated a story of [[Alma the Elder]], the former priest of a wicked king, who baptized his followers by immersion, \"having authority from the Almighty God\", and called his community of believers the \"church of God, or the church of Christ\".<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=18|verse=13|range=-17}}</ref> The book described the clergy in Alma's church as consisting of priests, who were unpaid and were to \"preach nothing save it were repentance and faith in the Lord\".<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=18|verse=20}}</ref> Alma later established many churches (or congregations), which were considered \"one church\" because \"there was nothing preached in all the churches except it were repentance and faith in God.\"<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=25|verse=22}}</ref> In addition to priests, the book mentions that the clergy of these churches also included teachers.<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=25|verse=21}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, in May 1829, a [[Revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]] by Smith described the \"church\" in informal terms: \"Behold, this is my doctrine: whosoever repenteth and cometh unto me, the same is my church: whosoever declareth more or less than this, the same is not of me, but is against me: therefore, he is not of my church.\"<ref>[[Book of Commandments]] 9:16</ref> Smith's further dictation of the [[Book of Mormon]] also stated that there were \"two churches only; the one is the church of the Lamb of God, and the other is the church of the devil\".<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=1 Nephi|chapter=14|verse=10}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the book's references to baptism and the organization of churches, Smith prayed for clarification and direction. Soon thereafter, in May 1829, Smith and [[Oliver Cowdery]] said they were visited by [[John the Baptist]] in angelic form, who conferred the [[Aaronic priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|Aaronic priesthood]] on them, which included the authority to baptize in Jesus Christ's name. Smith and Cowdery then baptized each other by immersion. They also baptized dozens of people, as early as June 1829.<ref>Smith, ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' 1:6, 59.</ref> These converts, however, did not belong to a formal church organization. Nevertheless, this community of believers referred to themselves as \"the Church of Christ\", and included converts in three New York towns: [[Fayette, New York|Fayette]], [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]], and [[Colesville, New York|Colesville]].\n\nIn June 1829, Smith dictated a revelation stating that \"in [the Book of Mormon] are all things written, concerning my church, my gospel, and my rock. Wherefore if you shall build up my church, and my gospel, and my rock, the gates of hell shall not prevail against you.\"<ref>[[Book of Commandments]] __:3\u20134.</ref> Some time between June and December 1829, Cowdery said he received a revelation about \"how he should build up his church & the manner thereof\". This revelation was called the \"[[Articles of the Church of Christ]]\", and it indicated that the church should ordain [[Priest (Latter Day Saints)|priests]] and [[Teacher (Latter Day Saints)|teachers]] \"according to the gifts & callings of God unto men\". The church was to meet regularly to partake of [[Sacrament (Mormonism)|bread and wine]]. Cowdery was described as \"an Apostle of Jesus Christ\". According to [[David Whitmer]], by April 1830, this informal \"Church of Christ\" had about six [[Elder (Latter Day Saints)|elders]] and 70 members.<ref name=\"Whitmer 1887 33\">{{Harv|Whitmer|1887|p=33}}</ref>\n\n==Organization of the church==\n{{See also|History of the Latter Day Saint movement#Organization of the Church of Christ}}\nOn April 6, 1830, [[Joseph Smith]], [[Oliver Cowdery]], and a group of approximately 30 believers met with the intention of formally organizing the Church of Christ into a legal institution. It is uncertain whether this occurred in the home of [[Peter Whitmer, Sr.]] in [[Fayette, New York]], or whether it occurred in the log home of [[Joseph Smith, Sr.]] near their property in [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]]. Soon after this formal organization, small [[Branch (Mormonism)|branches]] were formally established in Manchester, Fayette, and Colesville. Although the purpose was to effect a legal organization, it may have had no legal effect since no records of incorporation have been found in either the Manchester\u2013Palmyra area, the Fayette area, or in several other counties around this time period, as required by state law at the time: the church evidently did not follow the required legal formalities.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=224\u201325}}.</ref>\n\n===Location of the organization===\nPrior to 1834, all church publications and documents stated that the church was organized in the Smith log home in Manchester, New York.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=212\u2013219}}.</ref> The first Smith log home was located on the Samuel Jennings property in Palmyra, just north of the town's southern border and subsequent the Smith Manchester property.<ref>{{Harv|Berge|1985}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/history-maps/map-2?lang=eng|title=Church History Maps|website=ChurchofJesusChrist.org|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref> The Smiths may have constructed a second log home on their own property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://signaturebookslibrary.org/lucys-book-2/|title=Lucy's Book \u2013 02; note 76|last=|first=|date=|website=signaturebookslibrary.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-05|quote=The Smith family first lived in a house on the west end of Main Street in Palmyra. Between April 1819 and April 1820, they moved to a small cabin on Samuel Jennings\u2019s property just north of the Palmyra/Manchester township line. This log house [on their own property] was their third residence [since moving to] Palmyra and the first they had constructed.}}</ref>  Beginning in 1834, several church publications began to give the location of the organizational meeting as Fayette, at the home of [[Peter Whitmer, Sr.]] The Whitmer home had been the site of many other meetings near the same time period. After 1834, several official church accounts said the meeting was in Manchester<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|p=220}}</ref> and several eyewitnesses said the event took place in Manchester.<ref>Eye-witnesses include Joseph Smith {{Harv|Smith|1844}} (who had said in other statements that it was in Fayette), [[William Smith (Mormonism)|William Smith]] {{Harv|Smith|1883|p=14}}, [[Joseph Knight, Sr.]] {{Harv|Jessee|1976}}, and several non-believing Palmyra residents who had attended ({{Harvnb|Tucker|1867|p=58}}).</ref>\n\nIndependent researcher Michael Marquardt argues that the evidence suggests the organization occurred in Manchester, and that the confusion was likely due to the effect of memory tending to conflate memories of several meetings in Manchester and Fayette years earlier.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|p=221}}.</ref> Critics suggest that the location of the organization was intentionally changed in 1834 around the same time the church's name was changed to the \"Church of the Latter Day Saints\", in order to make it seem like the new church organization was different from the \"Church of Christ\", as a tactic to frustrate the church's creditors and avoid payment of debts.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=226\u2013228}}.</ref>\n\nThere is also evidence pointing to Fayette as the place of organization. For example, a headnote to the earliest known version of chapter XXII of the [[Book of Commandments]] says that the revelation was dictated in Fayette on April 6, 1830, after the church was organized.<ref>''Joseph Smith Papers'', (need citation).</ref> This was changed to \"Manchester\" when the book was published in 1833.<ref>Book of Commandments, chapter XXII, p. 45.</ref> Officially, the major denominations of the Latter Day Saint movement claim Fayette as the birthplace of the religion, and Smith's official history, begun in 1838, listed Fayette as the founding place.<ref>Joseph Smith ([[B. H. Roberts]] ed.). ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' '''1''':75\u201377.</ref> In 1887, one other eye-witness, [[David Whitmer]], recollected that the event occurred in his father's home in Fayette,<ref name=\"Whitmer 1887 33\"/> however, years earlier, in 1875, Whitmer had already told a reporter that the event occurred in Manchester.<ref>{{Harv|Whitmer|1875}}</ref> Marquardt argues that the event described by Whitmer in 1887 bears more resemblance to Fayette meetings such as the founding of the church's Fayette branch five days later on April 11, 1830.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=222\u201323}}.</ref>\n\nThe largest successor organization to the Church of Christ, the LDS Church, accepts Fayette as the official location of the organizing meeting.<ref>[[John K. Carmack]], [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1989/02/fayette-the-place-the-church-was-organized?lang=eng \"Fayette: The Place the Church Was Organized\"], ''[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]'', February 1989.</ref>\n\n===Events at the organization===\n\nBy later accounts, the April 6 organizational meeting was a [[charismatic (movement)|charismatic]] event, in which members of the congregation had visions, [[prophecy|prophesied]], [[glossalalia|spoke in tongues]], ecstatically shouted praises to the Lord, and fainted.<ref>Joseph Smith History, 1839 draft.</ref> At this meeting, the church formally ordained a lay ministry, with the priesthood offices of [[Deacon (Latter Day Saints)|deacon]], [[Teacher (Latter Day Saints)|teacher]], [[Priest (Latter Day Saints)|priest]], and [[Elder (Latter Day Saints)|elder]]. Smith and Cowdery, according to their 1831 account, were each ordained as \"an apostle of Jesus Christ, an elder of the church\".<ref>[http://josephsmithpapers.org/paperSummary?target=x4904 \"Articles and Covenants of the Church of Christ\"], ''[[Painesville Telegraph]]'', April 19, 1831.</ref> This account was edited in 1835 to state that Smith was ordained the \"First Elder\", and Oliver Cowdery was ordained the \"Second Elder\".<ref>[[Doctrine and Covenants|D&C]] 20:2\u20133 (LDS Church ed.).</ref>\n\n===First members of the church===\n{{main|Early participants in the Latter Day Saint movement}}\nAccording to the LDS Church, the first six members of the Church of Christ were:<ref>{{citation |chapter-url= http://www.lds.org/manual/church-history-in-the-fulness-of-times-student-manual/chapter-six-organization-of-the-church-of-jesus-christ |chapter= Chapter Six: Organization of the Church of Jesus Christ |title= Church History In the Fulness of Times Student Manual |year= 2003 |pages= 67\u201378 |publisher= LDS Church }}</ref><ref>Joseph Smith ([[B. H. Roberts]] (ed.), ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' '''1''':76, footnote.</ref>\n{{multiple image|total_width=600\n|caption_align=center|footer_align=center\n|width1=1342|height1=2244|image1=Olivercowdery-sm.jpg|caption1=[[Oliver Cowdery]]\n|width2=747|height2=1000|image2=Joseph Smith, Jr. portrait owned by Joseph Smith III.jpg|caption2=[[Joseph Smith]]\n|width3=500|height3=598|image3=Hyrum Smith ca 1880-1920.png|caption3=[[Hyrum Smith]]\n|width4=276|height4=315|image4=Samuel H. Smith.jpg|caption4=[[Samuel H. Smith (Latter Day Saints)|Samuel H. Smith]]\n|width5=280|height5=354|image5=David Witmer.JPG|caption5=[[David Whitmer]]\n|footer= Not shown: Peter Whitmer, Jr.}}\n* [[Oliver Cowdery]]\n* [[Joseph Smith]]\n* [[Hyrum Smith]]\n* [[Peter Whitmer, Jr.]]\n* [[Samuel H. Smith (Latter Day Saints)|Samuel H. Smith]]\n* [[David Whitmer]]\n\nEarly membership also included the [[Three Witnesses]] and the [[Eight Witnesses]] to the Book of Mormon and members of the extended Whitmer and [[Smith family (Latter Day Saints)|Smith families]]. Other early members included friends and acquaintances of the Smith and Whitmer families, such as [[Orrin Porter Rockwell]].\n\n==The name of the church==\n\n===Historical background===\n\nSmith's revelations authorized and commanded the organization of the \"Church of Christ\" in 1830, and in several of the revelations Smith said he received, God referred to the church by that name.<ref>LDS Church edition [[Doctrine and Covenants]] [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/21.11?lang=eng 21:11] (April 1830); [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/42.78?lang=eng 42:78] (February 1831); [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/107.59?lang=eng 107:59] (March 1835).</ref> Smith taught that this church was a restoration of the primitive Christian church established by Jesus in the 1st century AD. Smith also taught that this restoration occurred in the \"Latter Days\" of the world, that is, the time immediately prior to the [[Second Coming of Jesus]].<ref>{{Citation |editor-last=Roberts |editor-first=B.H |title=History of the Church |place=Salt Lake City, Utah |publisher=Deseret News |year=1904 |volume=3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=m2bEVgSvbS8C&printsec=frontcover&q |isbn=1-152-94824-5}}</ref>\n\n===Early changes===\nThe fact that a number of the churches of the Restoration Movement were also named the \"[[Churches of Christ|Church of Christ]]\" caused a considerable degree of confusion in the first years of the Latter Day Saint movement. Because of the distinct belief in the [[Book of Mormon]] among Smith's followers, people outside the church began to refer them as \"Mormonites\" or \"[[Mormon (word)|Mormons]].\" Smith and other church elders considered the name \"Mormon\" derogatory.<ref>[http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/NCMP1820-1846/id/5887 \"The Saints\"], ''[[Evening and Morning Star]]'', vol. 2, no. 20, pp. 158\u201359 (May 1834).</ref> In May 1834, the church adopted a resolution that the church would be known thereafter as \"The Church of the Latter Day Saints\".<ref name = 1834name/> At various times the church was also referred to as \"The Church of Jesus Christ\", \"The Church of God\",<ref name = othernames/> and \"The Church of Christ of Latter Day Saints\".<ref name = anderson/><ref name = black/>\n\nIn the late 1830s, Smith and those loyal to him founded a new headquarters in [[Far West, Missouri]]. At Far West in 1838, Smith announced a revelation renaming the organization the \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\".<ref name = 1838name1/><ref name = 1838name2/>\n\n===Later variations===\nUp to the time of [[Death of Joseph Smith|Smith's death]], the church was known alternatively as the \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" or the \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints\", that is, with or without a hyphen. After Smith's death, competing Latter Day Saint denominations organized under the leadership of a number of successors. The largest of these, led by [[Brigham Young]] and now based in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], continued using \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" until incorporating in 1851, when the church standardized the spelling of its name as \"[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\" (LDS Church).<ref>[http://www.jrcls.org/publications/perspectives/Lesson%20Plan%20re%20Law%20and%20Church%20as%20an%20Institution%20-%202.pdf Lesson: Law and the Church as an Institution].</ref> Followers of [[James J. Strang]] use the spelling of the [[public domain]] name, \"[[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite)|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]]\", as the name of their church.<ref>[https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131021180806/http://www.strangite.org/Name.htm \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints: Name of the Church\"], strangite.org, accessed 2011-04-07.</ref>\n\nThe name \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" was also used by members who recognized Smith's son, [[Joseph Smith III]], as his father's successor. The younger Smith became prophet-president of this group on April 6, 1860. However, the church incorporated in 1872 as the \"Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" (RLDS Church),<ref>''[[Saints' Herald]]'', 19 March 1972, p. 6.</ref> to distinguish it from the larger Utah church, at the time in the midst of federal issues related to [[plural marriage|polygamy]].<ref>[http://www.mhahome.org/about/mha_news.php \"A Brief History of Mormonism\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927094009/http://www.mhahome.org/about/mha_news.php |date=2011-09-27 }}, [[Mormon History Association]].</ref> In 2001, the RLDS Church changed its name again to \"[[Community of Christ]]\"\u2014consciously echoing the original \"Church of Christ\" name.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nThe [[Sidney Rigdon]] group dwindled until one of its elders, [[William Bickerton]], reorganized in 1862 under the name \"[[The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite)|The Church of Jesus Christ]]\".<ref name=\"Truth Spring Forth\">{{Citation |last=Lovalvo|first=V. James |title=It is Written: Truth Shall Spring Forth Out of the Earth|year=1980 |publisher= Midcal Publishers|location= Fresno, California|language= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages= 318|chapter= |url= |quote= }}</ref> Other Latter Day Saint denominations returned to the original name or a variation of the name, including the [[Church of Christ (Temple Lot)]], the [[Church of Jesus Christ (Cutlerite)]], and the now-extinct [[Church of Christ (Whitmerite)]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n==Succession claims==\n{{see also|Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)}}\nVirtually every Latter Day Saint denomination claims to be the rightful successor to the original Church of Christ and claims Joseph Smith as its founding prophet or first president. For example, the LDS Church,<ref>[https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/background-information/early-church-history \"Early Church History\"], mormonnewsroom.org, accessed 2015-10-22.</ref> Community of Christ,<ref>[http://www.cofchrist.org/history \"A Journey People\"], cofchrist.org, accessed 2015-10-22.</ref> Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite),<ref>[http://www.strangite.org/History.htm \"History and Succession\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131021180816/http://www.strangite.org/History.htm |date=2013-10-21 }}, strangite.org, accessed 2009-04-03.</ref> Church of Christ (Temple Lot),<ref>[http://www.churchofchrist-tl.org/about.html \"A Brief History of the Church of Christ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122181432/http://www.churchofchrist-tl.org/about.html |date=2016-11-22 }}, churchofchrist-tl.org, accessed 2015-10-22.</ref> and [[Church of Christ with the Elijah Message]]<ref>[http://www.elijahmessage.com/BriefHistoricalBackground.html Brief Historical Background of The Church of Christ: \"The Church With The Elijah Message\"], accessed 2010-06-30.</ref> all claim to have been organized by Smith on April 6, 1830, the date on which the Church of Christ was organized. Other denominations, such as The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite),<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071026080614/http://thechurchofjesuschrist.com/mission.htm \"Our Mission\"], thechurchofjesuschrist.com, accessed 2009-04-03.</ref> acknowledge that their organizations were created after this date, but nevertheless claim to be a re-establishment of the original church.\n\nIn an 1880 [[Kirtland Temple Suit|lawsuit]], an [[Ohio]] court held that the RLDS Church was the lawful successor to Smith's original Church of Christ.<ref name = KTS>[[Kirtland Temple Suit|''Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints v. Williams'']], Record T, 1880, p. 488, Court of Common Pleas, Lake County Courthouse, Painesville, Ohio.</ref> The court also explicitly held that the LDS Church was not the lawful successor because it \"has materially and largely departed from the faith, doctrines, law, ordinances and usages of the said original Church\".<ref name = KTS/> These holdings were preliminary findings of fact based on the RLDS Church's unopposed legal submissions; the court issued no final judgment on the matter because the case was dismissed.<ref>Kim L. Loving, \"Ownership of the Kirtland Temple: Legends, Lies, and Misunderstandings\", ''Journal of Mormon History'' '''30'''(2): 1\u201380 (Fall 2004); Eric Paul Rogers and R. Scott Glauser, \"The Kirtland Temple Suit and the Utah Church\", ''Journal of Mormon History'' '''30'''(2): 81\u201397 (Fall 2004).</ref>\n\nIn 1894, a [[federal United States court]] in [[Missouri]] held again that the RLDS Church was the lawful successor to the original church.<ref>[[Temple Lot Case|''Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints v. Church of Christ'']], 60 F. 937 (C.C.W.D. Mo. 1894).</ref> However, on appeal the [[Temple Lot Case|entire case]] was dismissed by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit]] without any discussion by the court of the issue of legal succession.<ref>[[Temple Lot Case|''Church of Christ in Missouri v. Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints'']], 70 F. 179 (8th Cir. 1895).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Joseph Smith\n |3=List of denominations in the Latter Day Saint movement\n}}\n*[[History of the Latter Day Saint movement]]\n*[[List of denominations in the Latter Day Saint movement]]\n{{Portal bar|Christianity|Latter Day Saint movement}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n*{{Citation\n |last=Berge \n |first=Dale L. \n |title=Archaeological Work at the Smith Log House \n |journal=[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] \n |volume=15 \n |issue=8 \n |date=August 1985 \n |pages=24 \n |url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1985/08/archaeological-work-at-the-smith-log-house\n |accessdate=June 30, 2010 \n |format= \n |df= \n}}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Carmack\n | first=John K.\n | authorlink=John K. Carmack\n | title=Fayette: The Place the Church was Organized\n | journal=[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]\n |volume=19\n |issue=2\n |date=February 1989\n | pages=15\u201319\n | url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1989/02/fayette-the-place-the-church-was-organized\n | accessdate=June 30, 2010\n | format=\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Jessee\n | first=Dean\n | authorlink=Dean C. Jessee\n | title=Joseph Knight's Recollection of Early Mormon History\n | journal=[[BYU Studies]]\n | volume=17\n | issue=1\n | year=1976\n | pages=35\n | url=http://byustudies.byu.edu/PDFLibrary/17.1Jessee.pdf\n | accessdate=June 30, 2010\n }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\n*{{Citation|last=Marquardt |first=H. Michael |title=An Appraisal of Manchester as Location for the Organization of the Church |journal=[[Sunstone Magazine|Sunstone]] |volume=87 |issue=2 |date=February 1992 |pages=49\u201357 |url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/087-49-57.pdf |accessdate=June 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311070653/https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/087-49-57.pdf |archivedate=March 11, 2012 }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Marquardt\n | first=H. Michael\n| title=The rise of Mormonism, 1816\u20131844\n | publisher=Xulon Press\n | year=2005\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Smith\n | first=Joseph\n | chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/44SmithHistoryoflds \n | chapter=History of the Latter Day Saints\n | editor-last=Rupp\n | editor-first=I. Daniel\n | title=He Pasa Ekklessia: An Original History of the Religious Denominations at Present Existing in the United States...\n |location=Philadelphia\n |publisher=J.Y. Humphreys\n |date=1844\n |pages=404\u2013410\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Smith\n | first=Lucy Mack\n | authorlink=Lucy Mack Smith\n | title=The History of Joseph Smith by His Mother\n | place=Lamoni, IA\n | publisher=RLDS Church\n | year=1908\n | title-link=The History of Joseph Smith by His Mother\n }} - ([https://books.google.com/books?id=jMmaOm3WSj4C&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Biographical+Sketches+of+Joseph+Smith+the+Prophet,+and+His+Progenitors+for+Many+Generations%22&source=bl&ots=4wp96PY9jU&sig=p7k804BSZAE3aGsVXBdv2f_PlGk&hl=en&ei=2HsrTJCDFdDmnQfds9ywDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CBIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q&f=false see also])\n*{{Citation\n | last=Smith\n | first=William\n | authorlink=William Smith (Mormonism)\n | title=William Smith on Mormonism: A True Account of the Origin of the Book of Mormon\n | place=Lamoni, Iowa\n | publisher=RLDS Church\n | year=1883\n | id=(ISBN not assigned)\n | url=http://www.olivercowdery.com/smithhome/1883Wilm.htm\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Tucker\n | first=Pomeroy\n | authorlink=Pomeroy Tucker\n | title=Origin, Rise and Progress of Mormonism\n | location=New York\n | year=1867\n | url=http://www.solomonspalding.com/docs1/1867TucA.htm\n | publisher=D. Appleton\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Whitmer\n | first=John C.\n | title=The Golden Tables\n | periodical=[[Chicago Times]]\n | date=August 7, 1875\n | url=http://www.sidneyrigdon.com/dbroadhu/IL/mischig.htm#080775\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Whitmer\n | first=David\n | authorlink=David Whitmer\n | title=An Address to All Believers in Christ By A Witness to the Divine Authenticity of the Book of Mormon\n | place=Richmond, Missouri\n | publisher=David Whitmer\n | year=1887\n | url=http://www.utlm.org/onlinebooks/address1.htm\n }}.\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Latter Day Saint movement}}\n{{LDS sects}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Church Of Christ (Latter Day Saints)}}\n[[Category:1830 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Church of Christ (Latter Day Saints)| ]]\n[[Category:History of the Latter Day Saint movement]]\n[[Category:Kirtland, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Nauvoo, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Pre-succession crisis sects in the Latter Day Saint movement| ]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1830]]\n[[Category:Seneca County, New York]]\n[[Category:Ontario County, New York]]\n[[Category:Joseph Smith]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the original name of the Latter Day Saint (LDS) church founded by Joseph Smith|other LDS and non\u2013LDS denominations that use \"Church of Christ\"|Church of Christ (disambiguation)}}\n{{redirects|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints|the present-day LDS Church|The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|the present-day Strangite church|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite)}}\n\n[[File:Peter whitmer log home.JPG|thumb|A reconstruction of the original Peter Whitmer home in Fayette, New York.]]\nThe '''Church of Christ''' was the original name of the [[Latter Day Saint]] church founded by [[Joseph Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sos.mo.gov/archives/resources/mormon|title=The Missouri Mormon War|website=www.sos.mo.gov}}</ref> Organized informally in 1829 in  [[New York (state)|New York]] and then formally on April 6, 1830, it was the first organization to implement the principles found in Smith's newly published [[Book of Mormon]], and thus represents the formal beginning of the [[Latter Day Saint movement]]. Later names for this organization included the '''Church of the Latter Day Saints''' (by 1834 resolution),<ref name = 1834name>[http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/NCMP1820-1846/id/5889 \"Minutes of a Conference\"], ''[[Evening and Morning Star]]'', vol. 2, no. 20, p. 160 (May 1832).</ref> the '''Church of Jesus Christ''',<ref name = othernames>[[Joseph Smith]] ([[B. H. Roberts]] (ed.)) ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' vol. 3, p. 24, footnote.</ref> the '''Church of God''',<ref name = othernames/> the '''Church of Christ of Latter Day Saints''',<ref name = anderson>[[Richard Lloyd Anderson]], [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1979/01/i-have-a-question \"I Have a Question: What changes have been made in the name of the Church?\"], ''[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]'', January 1979.</ref><ref name=black>[[Susan Easton Black]], [http://eom.byu.edu/index.php/Name_of_the_Church \"Name of the Church\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521034958/http://eom.byu.edu/index.php/Name_of_the_Church |date=2014-05-21 }} in [[Daniel H. Ludlow]] ed., ''[[Encyclopedia of Mormonism]]'' (Macmillan: New York, 1992) p. 979.</ref> and the '''Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints'''<!-- Do not change this name to \"The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints\". In the original text of the revelation, as referenced in this article, Smith wrote the name of the church \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" --> (by an 1838 revelation).<ref name = 1838name1>''Manuscript History of the Church'', LDS Church Archives, book A-1, p. 37; reproduced in Dean C. Jessee (comp.) (1989). ''The Papers of Joseph Smith: Autobiographical and Historical Writings'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Deseret Book) '''1''':302\u201303.</ref><ref name = 1838name2>H. Michael Marquardt and [[Wesley P. Walters]] (1994). ''Inventing Mormonism: Tradition and the Historical Record'' (Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books) p. 160.</ref>\n\nSmith and his associates asserted that the Church of Christ was a [[Restoration (Latter Day Saints)|restoration]] of the 1st-century [[Christianity|Christian]] church, which Smith claimed had fallen from God's favor and authority because of what he called a \"[[Great Apostasy]]\".  After [[Death of Joseph Smith|Smith's death]] in 1844, there was a [[Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)|crisis of authority]], with the majority of the members following [[Brigham Young]] to [[Utah Territory]], but with several smaller denominations remaining in Illinois or settling in Missouri and in other states. Each of the churches that resulted from this [[Schism (religion)|schism]] considers itself to be the rightful continuation of Smith's original \"Church of Christ\", regardless of the name they may currently bear ([[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church), [[Community of Christ]], [[The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite)]], [[Church of Christ (Temple Lot)]], etc.).\n\nThis church is unrelated to other bodies bearing the same name, including the [[United Church of Christ]], a [[Reformed churches|Reformed]] church body, and the [[Churches of Christ]], an offshoot of the [[Restoration movement|Campbellite movement]]. Today, there are several Latter Day Saint churches called \"Church of Christ\", largely within the [[Hedrickite]] branch of the movement.\n\n==Doctrinal development prior to 1830==\nThe first Latter Day Saint references to the \"church of Christ\" are found in passages of the [[Book of Mormon]] that Smith dictated from April to June 1829. During the course of this dictation, the outlines for a community of believers or church structure gradually became apparent. Such a structure would have authority from God, ordinances such as [[Baptism (Latter Day Saints)|baptism]], and ordained [[Priesthood (Mormonism)|clergy]]. Some time in April 1829, Smith dictated a story of [[Alma the Elder]], the former priest of a wicked king, who baptized his followers by immersion, \"having authority from the Almighty God\", and called his community of believers the \"church of God, or the church of Christ\".<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=18|verse=13|range=-17}}</ref> The book described the clergy in Alma's church as consisting of priests, who were unpaid and were to \"preach nothing save it were repentance and faith in the Lord\".<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=18|verse=20}}</ref> Alma later established many churches (or congregations), which were considered \"one church\" because \"there was nothing preached in all the churches except it were repentance and faith in God.\"<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=25|verse=22}}</ref> In addition to priests, the book mentions that the clergy of these churches also included teachers.<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=Mosiah|chapter=25|verse=21}}</ref>\n\nNevertheless, in May 1829, a [[Revelation (Latter Day Saints)|revelation]] by Smith described the \"church\" in informal terms: \"Behold, this is my doctrine: whosoever repenteth and cometh unto me, the same is my church: whosoever declareth more or less than this, the same is not of me, but is against me: therefore, he is not of my church.\"<ref>[[Book of Commandments]] 9:16</ref> Smith's further dictation of the [[Book of Mormon]] also stated that there were \"two churches only; the one is the church of the Lamb of God, and the other is the church of the devil\".<ref>{{sourcetext|source=Book of Mormon|book=1 Nephi|chapter=14|verse=10}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of the book's references to baptism and the organization of churches, Smith prayed for clarification and direction. Soon thereafter, in May 1829, Smith and [[Oliver Cowdery]] said they were visited by [[John the Baptist]] in angelic form, who conferred the [[Aaronic priesthood (Latter Day Saints)|Aaronic priesthood]] on them, which included the authority to baptize in Jesus Christ's name. Smith and Cowdery then baptized each other by immersion. They also baptized dozens of people, as early as June 1829.<ref>Smith, ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' 1:6, 59.</ref> These converts, however, did not belong to a formal church organization. Nevertheless, this community of believers referred to themselves as \"the Church of Christ\", and included converts in three New York towns: [[Fayette, New York|Fayette]], [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]], and [[Colesville, New York|Colesville]].\n\nIn June 1829, Smith dictated a revelation stating that \"in [the Book of Mormon] are all things written, concerning my church, my gospel, and my rock. Wherefore if you shall build up my church, and my gospel, and my rock, the gates of hell shall not prevail against you.\"<ref>[[Book of Commandments]] __:3\u20134.</ref> Some time between June and December 1829, Cowdery said he received a revelation about \"how he should build up his church & the manner thereof\". This revelation was called the \"[[Articles of the Church of Christ]]\", and it indicated that the church should ordain [[Priest (Latter Day Saints)|priests]] and [[Teacher (Latter Day Saints)|teachers]] \"according to the gifts & callings of God unto men\". The church was to meet regularly to partake of [[Sacrament (Mormonism)|bread and wine]]. Cowdery was described as \"an Apostle of Jesus Christ\". According to [[David Whitmer]], by April 1830, this informal \"Church of Christ\" had about six [[Elder (Latter Day Saints)|elders]] and 70 members.<ref name=\"Whitmer 1887 33\">{{Harv|Whitmer|1887|p=33}}</ref>\n\n==Organization of the church==\n{{See also|History of the Latter Day Saint movement#Organization of the Church of Christ}}\nOn April 6, 1830, [[Joseph Smith]], [[Oliver Cowdery]], and a group of approximately 30 believers met with the intention of formally organizing the Church of Christ into a legal institution. It is uncertain whether this occurred in the home of [[Peter Whitmer, Sr.]] in [[Fayette, New York]], or whether it occurred in the log home of [[Joseph Smith, Sr.]] near their property in [[Manchester (town), New York|Manchester]]. Soon after this formal organization, small [[Branch (Mormonism)|branches]] were formally established in Manchester, Fayette, and Colesville. Although the purpose was to effect a legal organization, it may have had no legal effect since no records of incorporation have been found in either the Manchester\u2013Palmyra area, the Fayette area, or in several other counties around this time period, as required by state law at the time: the church evidently did not follow the required legal formalities.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=224\u201325}}.</ref>\n\n===Location of the organization===\nPrior to 1834, all church publications and documents stated that the church was organized in the Smith log home in Manchester, New York.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=212\u2013219}}.</ref> The first Smith log home was located on the Samuel Jennings property in Palmyra, just north of the town's southern border and subsequent the Smith Manchester property.<ref>{{Harv|Berge|1985}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/history-maps/map-2?lang=eng|title=Church History Maps|website=ChurchofJesusChrist.org|access-date=2017-11-05}}</ref> The Smiths may have constructed a second log home on their own property.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://signaturebookslibrary.org/lucys-book-2/|title=Lucy's Book \u2013 02; note 76|last=|first=|date=|website=signaturebookslibrary.org|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-05|quote=The Smith family first lived in a house on the west end of Main Street in Palmyra. Between April 1819 and April 1820, they moved to a small cabin on Samuel Jennings\u2019s property just north of the Palmyra/Manchester township line. This log house [on their own property] was their third residence [since moving to] Palmyra and the first they had constructed.}}</ref>  Beginning in 1834, several church publications began to give the location of the organizational meeting as Fayette, at the home of [[Peter Whitmer, Sr.]] The Whitmer home had been the site of many other meetings near the same time period. After 1834, several official church accounts said the meeting was in Manchester<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|p=220}}</ref> and several eyewitnesses said the event took place in Manchester.<ref>Eye-witnesses include Joseph Smith {{Harv|Smith|1844}} (who had said in other statements that it was in Fayette), [[William Smith (Mormonism)|William Smith]] {{Harv|Smith|1883|p=14}}, [[Joseph Knight, Sr.]] {{Harv|Jessee|1976}}, and several non-believing Palmyra residents who had attended ({{Harvnb|Tucker|1867|p=58}}).</ref>\n\nIndependent researcher Michael Marquardt argues that the evidence suggests the organization occurred in Manchester, and that the confusion was likely due to the effect of memory tending to conflate memories of several meetings in Manchester and Fayette years earlier.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|p=221}}.</ref> Critics suggest that the location of the organization was intentionally changed in 1834 around the same time the church's name was changed to the \"Church of the Latter Day Saints\", in order to make it seem like the new church organization was different from the \"Church of Christ\", as a tactic to frustrate the church's creditors and avoid payment of debts.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=226\u2013228}}.</ref>\n\nThere is also evidence pointing to Fayette as the place of organization. For example, a headnote to the earliest known version of chapter XXII of the [[Book of Commandments]] says that the revelation was dictated in Fayette on April 6, 1830, after the church was organized.<ref>''Joseph Smith Papers'', (need citation).</ref> This was changed to \"Manchester\" when the book was published in 1833.<ref>Book of Commandments, chapter XXII, p. 45.</ref> Officially, the major denominations of the Latter Day Saint movement claim Fayette as the birthplace of the religion, and Smith's official history, begun in 1838, listed Fayette as the founding place.<ref>Joseph Smith ([[B. H. Roberts]] ed.). ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' '''1''':75\u201377.</ref> In 1887, one other eye-witness, [[David Whitmer]], recollected that the event occurred in his father's home in Fayette,<ref name=\"Whitmer 1887 33\"/> however, years earlier, in 1875, Whitmer had already told a reporter that the event occurred in Manchester.<ref>{{Harv|Whitmer|1875}}</ref> Marquardt argues that the event described by Whitmer in 1887 bears more resemblance to Fayette meetings such as the founding of the church's Fayette branch five days later on April 11, 1830.<ref>{{Harvtxt|Marquardt|2005|pp=222\u201323}}.</ref>\n\nThe largest successor organization to the Church of Christ, the LDS Church, accepts Fayette as the official location of the organizing meeting.<ref>[[John K. Carmack]], [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1989/02/fayette-the-place-the-church-was-organized?lang=eng \"Fayette: The Place the Church Was Organized\"], ''[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]'', February 1989.</ref>\n\n===Events at the organization===\n\nBy later accounts, the April 6 organizational meeting was a [[charismatic (movement)|charismatic]] event, in which members of the congregation had visions, [[prophecy|prophesied]], [[glossalalia|spoke in tongues]], ecstatically shouted praises to the Lord, and fainted.<ref>Joseph Smith History, 1839 draft.</ref> At this meeting, the church formally ordained a lay ministry, with the priesthood offices of [[Deacon (Latter Day Saints)|deacon]], [[Teacher (Latter Day Saints)|teacher]], [[Priest (Latter Day Saints)|priest]], and [[Elder (Latter Day Saints)|elder]]. Smith and Cowdery, according to their 1831 account, were each ordained as \"an apostle of Jesus Christ, an elder of the church\".<ref>[http://josephsmithpapers.org/paperSummary?target=x4904 \"Articles and Covenants of the Church of Christ\"], ''[[Painesville Telegraph]]'', April 19, 1831.</ref> This account was edited in 1835 to state that Smith was ordained the \"First Elder\", and Oliver Cowdery was ordained the \"Second Elder\".<ref>[[Doctrine and Covenants|D&C]] 20:2\u20133 (LDS Church ed.).</ref>\n\n===First members of the church===\n{{main|Early participants in the Latter Day Saint movement}}\nAccording to the LDS Church, the first six members of the Church of Christ were:<ref>{{citation |chapter-url= http://www.lds.org/manual/church-history-in-the-fulness-of-times-student-manual/chapter-six-organization-of-the-church-of-jesus-christ |chapter= Chapter Six: Organization of the Church of Jesus Christ |title= Church History In the Fulness of Times Student Manual |year= 2003 |pages= 67\u201378 |publisher= LDS Church }}</ref><ref>Joseph Smith ([[B. H. Roberts]] (ed.), ''[[History of the Church (Joseph Smith)|History of the Church]]'' '''1''':76, footnote.</ref>\n{{multiple image|total_width=600\n|caption_align=center|footer_align=center\n|width1=1342|height1=2244|image1=Olivercowdery-sm.jpg|caption1=[[Oliver Cowdery]]\n|width2=747|height2=1000|image2=Joseph Smith, Jr. portrait owned by Joseph Smith III.jpg|caption2=[[Joseph Smith]]\n|width3=500|height3=598|image3=Hyrum Smith ca 1880-1920.png|caption3=[[Hyrum Smith]]\n|width4=276|height4=315|image4=Samuel H. Smith.jpg|caption4=[[Samuel H. Smith (Latter Day Saints)|Samuel H. Smith]]\n|width5=280|height5=354|image5=David Witmer.JPG|caption5=[[David Whitmer]]\n|footer= Not shown: Peter Whitmer, Jr.}}\n* [[Oliver Cowdery]]\n* [[Joseph Smith]]\n* [[Hyrum Smith]]\n* [[Peter Whitmer, Jr.]]\n* [[Samuel H. Smith (Latter Day Saints)|Samuel H. Smith]]\n* [[David Whitmer]]\n\nEarly membership also included the [[Three Witnesses]] and the [[Eight Witnesses]] to the Book of Mormon and members of the extended Whitmer and [[Smith family (Latter Day Saints)|Smith families]]. Other early members included friends and acquaintances of the Smith and Whitmer families, such as [[Orrin Porter Rockwell]].\n\n==The name of the church==\n\n===Historical background===\n\nSmith's revelations authorized and commanded the organization of the \"Church of Christ\" in 1830, and in several of the revelations Smith said he received, God referred to the church by that name.<ref>LDS Church edition [[Doctrine and Covenants]] [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/21.11?lang=eng 21:11] (April 1830); [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/42.78?lang=eng 42:78] (February 1831); [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/107.59?lang=eng 107:59] (March 1835).</ref> Smith taught that this church was a restoration of the primitive Christian church established by Jesus in the 1st century AD. Smith also taught that this restoration occurred in the \"Latter Days\" of the world, that is, the time immediately prior to the [[Second Coming of Jesus]].<ref>{{Citation |editor-last=Roberts |editor-first=B.H |title=History of the Church |place=Salt Lake City, Utah |publisher=Deseret News |year=1904 |volume=3 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=m2bEVgSvbS8C&printsec=frontcover&q |isbn=1-152-94824-5}}</ref>\n\n===Early changes===\nThe fact that a number of the churches of the Restoration Movement were also named the \"[[Churches of Christ|Church of Christ]]\" caused a considerable degree of confusion in the first years of the Latter Day Saint movement. Because of the distinct belief in the [[Book of Mormon]] among Smith's followers, people outside the church began to refer them as \"Mormonites\" or \"[[Mormon (word)|Mormons]].\" Smith and other church elders considered the name \"Mormon\" derogatory.<ref>[http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/NCMP1820-1846/id/5887 \"The Saints\"], ''[[Evening and Morning Star]]'', vol. 2, no. 20, pp. 158\u201359 (May 1834).</ref> In May 1834, the church adopted a resolution that the church would be known thereafter as \"The Church of the Latter Day Saints\".<ref name = 1834name/> At various times the church was also referred to as \"The Church of Jesus Christ\", \"The Church of God\",<ref name = othernames/> and \"The Church of Christ of Latter Day Saints\".<ref name = anderson/><ref name = black/>\n\nIn the late 1830s, Smith and those loyal to him founded a new headquarters in [[Far West, Missouri]]. At Far West in 1838, Smith announced a revelation renaming the organization the \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\".<ref name = 1838name1/><ref name = 1838name2/>\n\n===Later variations===\nUp to the time of [[Death of Joseph Smith|Smith's death]], the church was known alternatively as the \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" or the \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints\", that is, with or without a hyphen. After Smith's death, competing Latter Day Saint denominations organized under the leadership of a number of successors. The largest of these, led by [[Brigham Young]] and now based in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]], continued using \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" until incorporating in 1851, when the church standardized the spelling of its name as \"[[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]\" (LDS Church).<ref>[http://www.jrcls.org/publications/perspectives/Lesson%20Plan%20re%20Law%20and%20Church%20as%20an%20Institution%20-%202.pdf Lesson: Law and the Church as an Institution].</ref> Followers of [[James J. Strang]] use the spelling of the [[public domain]] name, \"[[Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite)|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints]]\", as the name of their church.<ref>[https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131021180806/http://www.strangite.org/Name.htm \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints: Name of the Church\"], strangite.org, accessed 2011-04-07.</ref>\n\nThe name \"Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" was also used by members who recognized Smith's son, [[Joseph Smith III]], as his father's successor. The younger Smith became prophet-president of this group on April 6, 1860. However, the church incorporated in 1872 as the \"Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints\" (RLDS Church),<ref>''[[Saints' Herald]]'', 19 March 1972, p. 6.</ref> to distinguish it from the larger Utah church, at the time in the midst of federal issues related to [[plural marriage|polygamy]].<ref>[http://www.mhahome.org/about/mha_news.php \"A Brief History of Mormonism\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927094009/http://www.mhahome.org/about/mha_news.php |date=2011-09-27 }}, [[Mormon History Association]].</ref> In 2001, the RLDS Church changed its name again to \"[[Community of Christ]]\"\u2014consciously echoing the original \"Church of Christ\" name.{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}}\n\nThe [[Sidney Rigdon]] group dwindled until one of its elders, [[William Bickerton]], reorganized in 1862 under the name \"[[The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite)|The Church of Jesus Christ]]\".<ref name=\"Truth Spring Forth\">{{Citation |last=Lovalvo|first=V. James |title=It is Written: Truth Shall Spring Forth Out of the Earth|year=1980 |publisher= Midcal Publishers|location= Fresno, California|language= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages= 318|chapter= |url= |quote= }}</ref> Other Latter Day Saint denominations returned to the original name or a variation of the name, including the [[Church of Christ (Temple Lot)]], the [[Church of Jesus Christ (Cutlerite)]], and the now-extinct [[Church of Christ (Whitmerite)]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}}\n\n==Succession claims==\n{{see also|Succession crisis (Latter Day Saints)}}\nVirtually every Latter Day Saint denomination claims to be the rightful successor to the original Church of Christ and claims Joseph Smith as its founding prophet or first president. For example, the LDS Church,<ref>[https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/ldsnewsroom/eng/background-information/early-church-history \"Early Church History\"], mormonnewsroom.org, accessed 2015-10-22.</ref> Community of Christ,<ref>[http://www.cofchrist.org/history \"A Journey People\"], cofchrist.org, accessed 2015-10-22.</ref> Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Strangite),<ref>[http://www.strangite.org/History.htm \"History and Succession\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20131021180816/http://www.strangite.org/History.htm |date=2013-10-21 }}, strangite.org, accessed 2009-04-03.</ref> Church of Christ (Temple Lot),<ref>[http://www.churchofchrist-tl.org/about.html \"A Brief History of the Church of Christ] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161122181432/http://www.churchofchrist-tl.org/about.html |date=2016-11-22 }}, churchofchrist-tl.org, accessed 2015-10-22.</ref> and [[Church of Christ with the Elijah Message]]<ref>[http://www.elijahmessage.com/BriefHistoricalBackground.html Brief Historical Background of The Church of Christ: \"The Church With The Elijah Message\"], accessed 2010-06-30.</ref> all claim to have been organized by Smith on April 6, 1830, the date on which the Church of Christ was organized. Other denominations, such as The Church of Jesus Christ (Bickertonite),<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071026080614/http://thechurchofjesuschrist.com/mission.htm \"Our Mission\"], thechurchofjesuschrist.com, accessed 2009-04-03.</ref> acknowledge that their organizations were created after this date, but nevertheless claim to be a re-establishment of the original church.\n\nIn an 1880 [[Kirtland Temple Suit|lawsuit]], an [[Ohio]] court held that the RLDS Church was the lawful successor to Smith's original Church of Christ.<ref name = KTS>[[Kirtland Temple Suit|''Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints v. Williams'']], Record T, 1880, p. 488, Court of Common Pleas, Lake County Courthouse, Painesville, Ohio.</ref> The court also explicitly held that the LDS Church was not the lawful successor because it \"has materially and largely departed from the faith, doctrines, law, ordinances and usages of the said original Church\".<ref name = KTS/> These holdings were preliminary findings of fact based on the RLDS Church's unopposed legal submissions; the court issued no final judgment on the matter because the case was dismissed.<ref>Kim L. Loving, \"Ownership of the Kirtland Temple: Legends, Lies, and Misunderstandings\", ''Journal of Mormon History'' '''30'''(2): 1\u201380 (Fall 2004); Eric Paul Rogers and R. Scott Glauser, \"The Kirtland Temple Suit and the Utah Church\", ''Journal of Mormon History'' '''30'''(2): 81\u201397 (Fall 2004).</ref>\n\nIn 1894, a [[federal United States court]] in [[Missouri]] held again that the RLDS Church was the lawful successor to the original church.<ref>[[Temple Lot Case|''Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints v. Church of Christ'']], 60 F. 937 (C.C.W.D. Mo. 1894).</ref> However, on appeal the [[Temple Lot Case|entire case]] was dismissed by the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit]] without any discussion by the court of the issue of legal succession.<ref>[[Temple Lot Case|''Church of Christ in Missouri v. Reorganized Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints'']], 70 F. 179 (8th Cir. 1895).</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Joseph Smith\n |3=List of denominations in the Latter Day Saint movement\n}}\n*[[History of the Latter Day Saint movement]]\n*[[List of denominations in the Latter Day Saint movement]]\n{{Portal bar|Christianity|Latter Day Saint movement}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n*{{Citation\n |last=Berge \n |first=Dale L. \n |title=Archaeological Work at the Smith Log House \n |journal=[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]] \n |volume=15 \n |issue=8 \n |date=August 1985 \n |pages=24 \n |url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1985/08/archaeological-work-at-the-smith-log-house\n |accessdate=June 30, 2010 \n |format= \n |df= \n}}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Carmack\n | first=John K.\n | authorlink=John K. Carmack\n | title=Fayette: The Place the Church was Organized\n | journal=[[Ensign (LDS magazine)|Ensign]]\n |volume=19\n |issue=2\n |date=February 1989\n | pages=15\u201319\n | url=https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/study/ensign/1989/02/fayette-the-place-the-church-was-organized\n | accessdate=June 30, 2010\n | format=\n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Jessee\n | first=Dean\n | authorlink=Dean C. Jessee\n | title=Joseph Knight's Recollection of Early Mormon History\n | journal=[[BYU Studies]]\n | volume=17\n | issue=1\n | year=1976\n | pages=35\n | url=http://byustudies.byu.edu/PDFLibrary/17.1Jessee.pdf\n | accessdate=June 30, 2010\n }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.\n*{{Citation|last=Marquardt |first=H. Michael |title=An Appraisal of Manchester as Location for the Organization of the Church |journal=[[Sunstone Magazine|Sunstone]] |volume=87 |issue=2 |date=February 1992 |pages=49\u201357 |url=https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/087-49-57.pdf |accessdate=June 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311070653/https://www.sunstonemagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/sbi/articles/087-49-57.pdf |archivedate=March 11, 2012 }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last=Marquardt\n | first=H. Michael\n| title=The rise of Mormonism, 1816\u2013184